  <glossary>
    <definition id="import-auto-id3007462"><term>work-energy theorem</term> <meaning id="fs-id2070291">if one or more external forces act upon a rigid object, causing its kinetic energy to change from <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>KE</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>1</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> to <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mtext>KE</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>2</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math>, then the work <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>W</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> done by the net force is equal to the change in kinetic energy</meaning></definition>
    <definition id="import-auto-id1771451"><term>rotational kinetic energy</term> <meaning id="fs-id2383989">the kinetic energy due to the rotation of an object. This is part of its total kinetic energy</meaning></definition>
  </glossary>
